# MR Risk Analyzer (GitLab) template.
#
# Triages a GitLab MR as rubber-stamp-safe (approve) or needing a focused Pair
# Review (Human Input Needed comment with handoff links). Shares the
# platform-neutral rubric (`kb://skills/code-review/risk-analysis-core.md`) with
# the GitHub PR Risk Analyzer; only the GitLab surface mechanics differ.
#
# Before applying:
#   1. Create/apply a GitLab environment using `gitlab-cloud.yaml.template`;
#      substitute its environment ID for `<GITLAB_ENVIRONMENT_ID>` below.
#      See `guides/cloud/gitlab-environment-setup.md`.
#   2. If you run the GitLab Pair Reviewer, apply `mr-pair-reviewer.yaml.template`
#      first, then paste its expert ID into `<PAIR_REVIEWER_GITLAB_EXPERT_ID>` in
#      the system prompt below. If you do not run it, delete the Human Input
#      Needed handoff links from the rubric output instead of filling the placeholder.
#   3. Edit the opted-out repos / sub-directories list in the system prompt to
#      match your org's sensitive areas.
#   4. GitLab has no `type: github` trigger equivalent. To run automatically,
#      create a GitLab custom webhook (`auggie cloud webhook create --type gitlab`),
#      configure it in the project (Merge request events + Comment events for the
#      `cosmos risk-analysis` re-analysis path), and launch the expert from it.
#      Runtime subscriptions filter by payload shape, not by webhook ID. Until
#      that is wired, launch the expert manually with an MR URL.
apiVersion: poseidon.augmentcode.com/v1alpha1
kind: ExpertBundle
metadata:
  name: mr-risk-analyzer
spec:
  expert:
    displayName: MR Risk Analyzer (GitLab)
    description: Auto-triages a GitLab MR as rubber-stamp-safe or needing a focused Pair Review; re-analyzes on a `cosmos risk-analysis` MR note.
    visibility: tenant
    systemPrompt: |-
      <include src="kb://expert-templates/prompts/mr-risk-analyzer.md" />

      # Opted-out repos and sub-directories — always require full review

      Edit this list for your repository. The categories below are the recommended pattern; replace the example paths with the sensitive areas of your codebase.

      ## Opted-out repos (entire repo always requires review)
      <GROUP>/<PROJECT_NAME>

      ## Sub-directories in `<GROUP>/<MAIN_PROJECT>` that always require full review

      ### Security & Trust
      path/to/auth
      path/to/security
      path/to/secrets

      ### Billing & Payments
      path/to/billing

      ### Access Control & Gateways
      path/to/api_proxy
      path/to/sandbox

      ### Infrastructure & Deploy
      deploy/
      infra/
      .gitlab/

      ### Data & Compliance
      path/to/data_lifecycle

      ### Agent Configuration files
      .augment/
      **/AGENTS.md

      # Pair Reviewer handoff configuration

      Replace this placeholder before applying. The shared rubric derives the
      webapp origin from `session-metadata.md` at runtime, but the Pair Reviewer
      expert ID is tenant-specific.

      - Pair Reviewer (GitLab) expert ID: <PAIR_REVIEWER_GITLAB_EXPERT_ID>
    model: claude-opus-4-8
    includeDefaultSystemPrompt: true
    capabilities:
      - WEB_ACCESS
      - CUSTOM_WEBHOOK
    environment:
      id: <GITLAB_ENVIRONMENT_ID>
      resources:
        cpuCores: 2
        memoryMib: 4096
    initialMessages: []
    userInstructions: ""
    placeholderText: GitLab MR URL
    workerExpertIds: []
    useAllExpertsAsWorkers: false
  triggers: []
